Coppola v.
Variety Headed to Trial
-----------------------

Every so often, a court ruling catches me off guard. Francis Ford
Coppola=E2=80=99s defamation lawsuit against Variety, which I had pegged as=
 a vanity project=E2=80=94just like Megalopolis=E2=80=94is moving forward, =
thanks to a judge=E2=80=99s ruling that the legendary filmmaker has a proba=
bility of prevailing.
=C2=A0

If you recall, Variety had followed up on reports from other outlets allegi=
ng that Coppola tried to kiss some scantily clad female extras during the f=
ilming of last year=E2=80=99s
Megalopolis. The Jay Penske-owned publication obtained video of the alleged=
 incident, and interviewed crewmembers who accused the 85-year-old of being=
 unprofessional on set. In his $15 million claim, Coppola asserted that Var=
iety improperly relied on anonymous sources. Variety responded with an anti=
-SLAPP motion, questioning how Coppola could possibly win a case, given tha=
t he conceded he kissed and hugged actresses, appeared in multiple shots hi=
mself,
and didn=E2=80=99t dispute the authenticity of the published videos or the =
lack of intimacy coordinators on set. What, Variety=E2=80=99s attorneys wan=
ted to know, was defamatory? What would be the basis for damages?

Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Christopher Lui has provided an answer. In=
 a 19-page decision (read
it in full here ( https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/25544097-coppola-=
slapp-ruling/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F25%=
2F25%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F25%2F25%29=
&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42=
abd12a )), Lui calls out Variety for reporting that Coppola inadvertently i=
nserted himself into shots, which could imply he was an incompetent directo=
r. Coppola, in a declaration in the case, had said he was deliberately evok=
ing a Studio 54 nightclub vibe, where celebrities would naturally appear. V=
ariety=E2=80=99s sources from the movie set, Coppola claimed, knew this. Be=
cause the article impugned Coppola=E2=80=99s professionalism, the judge say=
s this could rise to
defamation per se=E2=80=94meaning Coppola wouldn=E2=80=99t need to prove sp=
ecial damages.

As for the video=E2=80=A6 did it show kissing, or just Coppola leaning in a=
nd whispering? Were the extras genuinely uncomfortable? Variety spoke to cr=
ewmembers who interpreted the events one way, but Judge Lui noted that fram=
ing a statement as an opinion doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily shield it from be=
ing considered a provably false fact. As for the claim that the videos
=E2=80=9Cappear to corroborate=E2=80=9D unwanted kissing? Lui says let a ju=
ry decide. Of course, Variety would prefer to let its readers decide.=C2=A0

So, this one is likely headed to trial=E2=80=94though an appeal has already=
 been filed, since anti-SLAPP rulings in California can be immediately chal=
lenged. If it doesn=E2=80=99t settle, look for a possible courtroom showdow=
n between one of the world=E2=80=99s most famous directors and one of Holly=
wood=E2=80=99s largest trade
publications. Naturally, all the Penske outlets are covering this ruling as=
 aggressively as they are the Lively-Baldoni fight. Just kidding.

